         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
             <ab>
                <lb n="1"/><w lemma="τόπος">τόποϲ</w> <w lemma="αὐράριος">αὐραρίω<milestone unit="block"/>ν</w> <w lemma="Βένετος"><expan><abbr>Βενέτω</abbr><ex>ν</ex></expan></w>.
</ab>     </div>
         
         
         
         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve">
           <p>Place of Blue aurarii</p></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Aurarii appear on three other seats in the Miletus theatre: <title>I. Milet</title> 940.I.b-d, available at <title>PHI</title> <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/351670">351670</ref>, 
               <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/351671">351671</ref>, <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/351672">351672</ref>.   
               Alan Cameron (loc cit.) suggested that they were cheerleaders; 
               Roueché, loc. cit. read the term as meaning goldsmiths.   
               C. Zuckerman, <ref target="https://www.persee.fr/doc/rebyz_0766-5598_2000_num_58_1_1986">Le cirque, l'argent et le peuple. 
                  À propos d'une inscription du Bas-Empire (2000)</ref> suggests, very convincingly, that they were the treasurers of the colours, 
               so holding and dispensing their funds.</p> 
         </div>
         
